# Liver

> The liver is the **largest solid organ in the body** (~1.5 kg), occupying the right upper quadrant under the diaphragm. It performs over 500 functions including bile production, detoxification, protein synthesis, glycogen storage, and cholesterol metabolism.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- Protected by: [[Ribs]] (under right dome of diaphragm, ribs 5–10)
- Relations: [[Stomach]] (left lobe), [[Gallbladder]] (inferior), [[Inferior Vena Cava]] (posterior groove)
- Blood supply (dual):
  - **Portal vein** (75%) — nutrient-rich from [[Portal System]]
  - **Hepatic artery proper** (25%) — oxygenated from [[Celiac Trunk]]
- Drains into: hepatic veins → [[Inferior Vena Cava]] → [[Heart]]
- Bile flows: bile canaliculi → hepatic ducts → common hepatic duct → [[Gallbladder]] (via cystic duct) or [[Small Intestine]] (via common bile duct)

## 🗂️ Anatomical Lobes

| Lobe | Location | Notes |
|------|----------|-------|
| **Right lobe** | Large, right side | Separated from left by falciform ligament (anatomical) or middle hepatic vein (functional) |
| **Left lobe** | Smaller, left of falciform | Overlies stomach |
| **Caudate lobe** | Posterior (segment I) | Drains directly into IVC; may enlarge in Budd-Chiari |
| **Quadrate lobe** | Between GB and falciform | Functionally = left lobe |

## 🗂️ Couinaud Segments (Surgical)
8 functionally independent segments (I–VIII), each with its own portal triad (portal vein + hepatic artery + bile duct) and hepatic vein drainage — enables segmental resection.

## 🗂️ Key Functions

| Function | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| **Bile production** | ~500–1000 mL/day; bile salts emulsify fats for absorption |
| **Protein synthesis** | Albumin, clotting factors (II, VII, IX, X + protein C, S), fibrinogen; NOT factor VIII (endothelium) or vWF |
| **Gluconeogenesis + glycogenolysis** | Maintains blood glucose between meals |
| **Detoxification** | CYP450 enzymes metabolise drugs, alcohol, ammonia → urea |
| **Cholesterol metabolism** | Synthesis + bile salt conjugation |
| **Iron storage** | Ferritin; haem catabolism → bilirubin → bile |

## 🔑 Hepatic Triad (Portal Triad)
Each lobule has portal triads at corners: **portal vein + hepatic artery + bile duct**. Blood flows portal vein → sinusoids → central vein → hepatic veins. Bile flows opposite direction: hepatocytes → canaliculi → bile ducts.

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Hepatitis** — viral (A–E), autoimmune, alcoholic; raised transaminases (AST, ALT); jaundice
- **Cirrhosis** — end-stage liver fibrosis; causes: alcohol, NAFLD, viral hepatitis, PBC, PSC, haemochromatosis, Wilson's; complications: portal hypertension, varices, ascites, hepatic encephalopathy, hepatorenal syndrome, HCC
- **Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC)** — risk: cirrhosis + hepatitis B; AFP raised; treat: ablation, resection, TACE, sorafenib, transplant
- **Jaundice** — pre-hepatic (haemolysis), hepatic (hepatitis, cirrhosis), post-hepatic (obstructive: gallstones, cancer); unconjugated vs. conjugated bilirubin
- **Liver abscess** — pyogenic (E. coli — portal spread from appendicitis/diverticulitis) or amoebic (Entamoeba histolytica); RUQ pain + fever + raised ALP
- **Liver failure** — coagulopathy (↓clotting factors), encephalopathy, hypoglycaemia; PT/INR best marker of synthetic function
- **Liver transplantation** — indicated for acute liver failure, cirrhosis (MELD score), HCC (Milan criteria)


